article.description:
Hedo Turkoglu scored 23 points, Dwight
Howard added 15 points and 13 rebounds, and the Magic beat
the Hawks 108-101 on Sunday.
article.headline: Magic put six in double figures, get third straight win
article.linkText: Magic put six in double figures, get third straight win
article.story:
ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- The rebuilt Orlando Magic definitely have it together when playing on their home floor. Now it's a matter of taking the new act on the road. Orlando beat Atlanta 108-101 Sunday, improving to 7-1 at home since trading for Darko Milicic, Carlos Arroyo and Trevor Ariza. The Magic are 1-10 on the road in that same period, with games at Chicago and Minnesota up next. "We definitely play with a lot more confidence at home," Magic coach Brian Hill said after his team won its third in a row overall. "With the new guys, we have a lot of young players that feed off the energy of our crowd and when they don't get that on the road, it obviously takes away some of their confidence." The Magic shot a season-high 59.7 percent and put six players in double figures. "Everybody is happy with each other, everybody is passing the ball, there's a lot of good vibes and it shows on the court," said DeShawn Stevenson, who had 12 points for the Magic. Hedo Turkoglu led the way with 23 points, Dwight Howard and Jameer Nelson had 15 apiece, and Milicic and Keyon Dooling each had 13. "We still think there is a chance to make the playoffs and we're going to play like we still have a chance," added Milicic. There are no such thoughts for Atlanta, which has lost four straight and eight of its last nine. The Hawks got 20 points from Al Harrington, 19 from Joe Johnson and 18 from Josh Childress, but ran out of gas after pulling within 89-85 with just over 6 minutes left in the game. "The Magic just beat us. They did what they had to do to protect their home court," Harrington said. "We've got to keep trying to win and continue to play the right way." The Hawks shot only 40 percent from the field, though they did get 23 offensive rebounds. That helped keep them within striking range most of the game, but when the starting five got tired, there wasn't much help. Childress and rookie Marvin Williams, who had 13 points, provided the only contributions from the bench. "Everybody is tired this time of year," Hawks coach Mike Woodson said. "Unfortunately, we don't have the luxury of subbing a lot of guys in and out. We had some chances at the end, but we're just not getting key stops when we need them."

Game notes
Orlando has shot better than 50 percent in its last four games. ... Johnson is only 12-of-35 (34.2 percent) in his last two games. ... The Magic honored Dennis Scott, the team's all-time leading 3-point shooter, during a ceremony at the end of the first quarter. Scott is now a radio analyst for the Hawks. ... Magic C Tony Battie is 25-of-36 (69.4 percent) from the field in his last five games.
